title: Made all of the GraphNode values optional
body:
When passing data to a d3 structure the data can be very flexible.
The current interface of the GraphNode requires many data attributes
to be present, most of which aren't required to draw the
visualization. In fact, d3 calculates some of them itself, so passing
them to the GraphNode would be redundant.

In this example http://bl.ocks.org/mbostock/4063269#flare.json, Mike
Bostock uses the attribute className to identify name and packageName
to identify color in the GraphNode. This means that he doesn't only
ignore all of the attributes DefintelyTyped provides, but comes up
with his own attributes. This means that the data passed in could in
fact be a hashmap/js object type with arbitrary attributes. It's only
when the data is used with d3 methods to identify what attribute
represents size/color etc... that the type becomes relevant.

So either the GraphNode should be less restrictive (or in fact an
arbitrary hashmap) or I've misunderstood some core concept.

You don't have to necessarily merge this pull request, if I'm right
some parts will have to be rewritten (GraphNodes seem to be used
everywhere), but hopefully it might spark some discussion.

title: Update React v0.13.0 definitions for RC2
body:
Added: - `React.cloneElement` (fixes #3795) - `React.addons.createFragment` - `setState(f: (prevState: S, props: P) => S, callback?: () => any)` (transactional `setState`) - `ref: (component: T) => any` (callback refs) It's common to reference the type of generic React elements. With the previous type definitions, `React.ReactElement

` specifically referred to "modern" elements created from modern component classes, which is confusing. So now we have: changed: `React.ReactElementBase` to `React.ReactElement

` (added `React.ModernElement

`) changed: `React.ComponentClassBase

` to `React.ComponentClass

` (added `React.ModernComponentClass`) With callback refs, we want to be able to infer the type of the component passed in the callback. To do so, extend `React.Props` like so: ``` ts interface MyProps extends React.Props {} class MyComponent extends React.Component {} React.createElement(MyComponent, { ref: (component: MyComponent) => null }); // ok React.createElement(MyComponent, { ref: (component: React.DOMComponent) => null }); // fail ``` cc @pspeter3, @jbrantly

Current definition is `T => any`.

Current definition operatable messaging value in `done/fail/always` methods.

title: Fix trap suggestion
body:
Sorry, my previous fix has a problem!
jQuery official specification is wrong and trap!

> http://api.jquery.com/deferred.done/
> deferred.done( doneCallbacks [, doneCallbacks ] ) **Returns: Deferred**

Definable this code by official specification, but this code error occurs.

``` js
$.Deferred().done().resolve(); // done
$.Deferred().promise().done().resolve(); // runtime error
$.Deferred().then(function () { }).done().resolve(); // runtime error
```

This problem has not been covered by tests.
So I added a test.

Total diff.

body:
**improved bluebird's Promise.promisify definition**
  now returns a function that returns a promise in most circumstances.

**new hapi definition, for v8.2.0**
also totally redid the hapi definition, as it did not conform to the current version, v8.2.0 (missing and invalid definitions)

**removed old hapi definition**
I would have left the old hapi definition but needed to remove it:  there seems to be a typescript d.ts bug where if two d.ts files export the same ambient module ("hapi" in this case), they conflict with each other during typescript compile. (got `An export assignment cannot be used in a module with other exported elements` error)

title: Define proper jqLite interface instead of JQuery
body:
Closes #2734
Closes #3528

Calling angular.element(), when jQuery is not loaded, returns a jqLite instance, a stripped-down version of jQuery. It has fewer methods and some of them do not handle the same parameters as jQuery would.

A jqLite object is never an augmented jQuery object, as it is implied today. They are mutually exclusive.

As a result, no dependency on JQuery anymore. This has the benefit of avoiding conflict with protractor, which also defines a $ symbol.

title: Fix the signature of D3.Transition.each
body:
Only the first argument of `D3.Transition.Transition.each` is optional, while the callback parameter is mandatory. Setting both parameters optional does not produce the expected behavior. We should use overload here.

See API reference of [transition.each](https://github.com/mbostock/d3/wiki/Transitions#each):

> ### transition.each([type, ]listener)
> 
> If type is specified, adds a listener for transition events, supporting "start", "end" and "interrupt" events. The listener will be invoked for each individual element in the transition.
> ...
> If type is not specified, behaves similarly to `selection.each`: immediately invokes the specified function for each element in the current transition, passing in the current datum `d` and index `i`, with the `this` context of the current DOM element.
